<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="recruitment-funnel-optimization">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>hr-recruiter</domain>
    <summary>Stage-by-stage framework for measuring and improving candidate conversion across six hiring phases with key metrics, industry benchmarks, and concrete optimization levers.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>recruitment</tag>
      <tag>funnel</tag>
      <tag>hiring</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>conversion</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Recruitment Funnel Optimization</title>

    <summary>A stage-by-stage framework for measuring and improving candidate conversion across six hiring phases: Awareness, Application, Screening, Interview, Offer, and Onboarding. Each stage has a key metric, industry benchmark, and concrete optimization levers. Apply it when time-to-fill or offer-acceptance rate deviates from benchmarks.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>High candidate drop-off at any single stage inflates time-to-fill and cost-per-hire without a visible root cause. Funnel visibility converts a vague "we're struggling to hire" complaint into a specific, addressable bottleneck — e.g., offer-acceptance at 70% (below 85% benchmark) triggered by compensation gap, solvable with market benchmarking.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Time-to-fill exceeds 45 days for a role type that should close faster.</item>
        <item>Offer acceptance rate drops below 85%.</item>
        <item>No current tracking of conversion rates between funnel stages.</item>
        <item>Preparing a quarterly or monthly recruiting metrics report.</item>
        <item>Post-mortem on a failed hire or stalled pipeline.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single isolated open role with no historical data — benchmark comparison is meaningless.</item>
        <item>Roles with structurally different funnels (executive search, agency-sourced, internal transfer) — apply role-segmented benchmarks instead.</item>
        <item>Optimizing volume only without tracking quality-of-hire — risks flooding the funnel with mismatched candidates.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="funnel-stages">
      <p>Six-stage hiring funnel with benchmark conversion rates and optimization levers per stage.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Track conversion rate at every funnel stage; a stage without a metric cannot be optimized.</statement>
        <rationale>Funnel leakage is invisible without conversion data. ATS and career-page analytics provide the raw counts; the ratio reveals the bottleneck.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="awareness">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Measure career page views and apply-click rate as the Awareness-to-Application indicator.</statement>
          <rationale>No benchmark exists for awareness volume alone; what matters is whether visitors convert to applicants.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Optimization levers: career page SEO, employer brand content, job board and aggregator distribution, employee referral program, social media presence.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="application">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Application conversion benchmark is 8-12%; below 8% signals JD friction or application UX problems.</statement>
          <rationale>A long application form, missing mobile support, or unclear JD causes candidates to abandon before submitting.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Optimization levers: simplify application to under 5 minutes, remove non-essential fields, ensure mobile-friendly form, send auto-response on submit.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="screening">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Screen-to-interview conversion benchmark is 20-30%; outside this range signals sourcing quality or criteria clarity problems.</statement>
          <rationale>Below 20% means sourcing is generating noise; above 30% may mean screening criteria are too loose.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Optimization levers: define clear screening criteria before posting, automate initial resume pass, schedule phone screen within 1 week, send timely rejections.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="interview">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Interview-to-offer conversion benchmark is 15-25%; deviation indicates process efficiency or evaluation consistency issues.</statement>
          <rationale>Too low means the interview process is filtering beyond the intended bar or taking too long. Too high may indicate insufficient rigor.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Optimization levers: structured interview process, calibrated interviewers, scheduling within 1 week, positive candidate experience, timely feedback.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="offer">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Offer acceptance benchmark is 85-95%; below 85% requires root-cause analysis of declined reasons before adjusting compensation.</statement>
          <rationale>Declines split across compensation, competing offers, and role/location mismatches. Each has a different fix; conflating them wastes budget.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Optimization levers: issue offer within 48 hours of decision, make a personal hiring-manager call, prepare for negotiation with defined limits, preempt competing offers with verbal commitments.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="onboarding">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Track 90-day retention as the funnel's terminal metric; target 90%+.</statement>
          <rationale>A hire who leaves in 90 days represents the full recruiting cost with zero return. Onboarding quality is a recruiting metric, not only an HR metric.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="key-metrics">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Report time-to-fill, cost-per-hire, and quality-of-hire alongside conversion rates; volume metrics alone mask quality degradation.</statement>
        <rationale>Optimizing application volume without tracking quality-of-hire floods the funnel with mismatched candidates and inflates downstream costs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Metric targets: time-to-fill under 45 days; cost-per-hire under $4,000; offer acceptance above 85%; quality-of-hire (meeting expectations at 1 year) above 80%.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="diagnosis">
      <p>Structured approach for identifying and fixing the root cause of candidate drop-off at any funnel stage.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Diagnose each stage with one question: is the metric above or below benchmark? If below, list the top 3 possible causes before acting.</statement>
        <rationale>Acting on the first plausible cause (usually compensation) without data repeats the diagnosis cycle after the fix fails.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="diagnosis-questions">
        <p>Awareness: Are we attracting enough candidates? — check career page analytics; if low, improve employer brand or distribution.</p>
        <p>Application: Are they applying? — check apply-click rate; if low, simplify application form and clarify JD.</p>
        <p>Screening: Are we screening efficiently? — check time-to-screen and screen-to-interview; if slow, add automation or tighten criteria.</p>
        <p>Interview: Are interviews predictive? — check interview-to-offer rate and post-hire performance; if low, add structured process.</p>
        <p>Offer: Are offers accepted? — check acceptance rate and decline reasons; segment by compensation vs. competing offer vs. role fit.</p>
        <p>Onboarding: Are hires staying? — track 90-day retention; if low, audit onboarding quality and day-30/60 check-ins.</p>
      </section>

      <example type="good">
        <note>Offer acceptance dropped from 90% to 70%. Decline analysis: 4 for compensation (40%), 3 competing offers accepted faster (30%), 2 changed mind on role (20%), 1 location (10%). Fix: market benchmarking for compensation, verbal offer before written for speed, improved JD clarity for role expectations. Three months later: acceptance back to 88%.</note>
      </example>

      <section name="antipatterns">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Optimizing conversion at one stage without checking impact on downstream quality.</description>
          <reason>Broadening screening criteria raises screen-to-interview rate but may lower interview-to-offer rate and quality-of-hire; the funnel looks better while the outcome worsens.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Using industry-wide benchmarks for specialized or executive roles.</description>
          <reason>A senior ML engineer role has structurally different conversion rates than a sales SDR role; applying the same benchmarks produces false alarms and missed signals.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Fixing symptoms (e.g., adding more job boards) without diagnosing the root stage.</description>
          <reason>If drop-off is at offer acceptance, increasing top-of-funnel volume only magnifies the waste; the fix must match the broken stage.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>No candidate-experience survey, relying only on internal funnel data.</description>
          <reason>Candidates who drop off after screening often don't give visible signals; exit surveys surface real reasons (slow response, poor communication) that internal data misses.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-workflow">
      <p>Drive funnel optimization as a five-stage pipeline owned by `faion-recruiter-agent`. Stage 1 (data ingestion, sonnet) pulls ATS exports + ad spend + career-page analytics into a unified dataset. Stage 2 (anomaly detection, sonnet) compares this period vs trailing 4 against role-family benchmarks; flags only deltas with p &lt; 0.05 or absolute swing &gt; 5pp. Stage 3 (root-cause hypothesis, opus) — for each flag, generates 2-3 candidate causes with required evidence to confirm. Stage 4 (action recommendations, opus) — only proposes actions whose expected lift is computed against the hypothesis. Stage 5 (A/B plan, sonnet) — converts each action into a measurable test with sample-size math.</p>

      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <list>
          <item>`faion-recruiter-agent` — primary; owns ingestion, anomaly detection, recommendations.</item>
          <item>`faion-research-agent (mode: market)` — competitive comp benchmarking when the leak is offer-stage.</item>
          <item>`faion-employer-brand-agent` — owns top-of-funnel actions (career page, employer-brand content).</item>
          <item>`general-purpose` reviewer (sonnet, fresh context) — challenges root-cause logic; rejects unfalsifiable hypotheses.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="prompt-patterns">
        <p>Anomaly detection: Inputs: this-period funnel JSON + trailing-4-period funnel JSON + role-family benchmarks (attached). For each stage, compute conversion + 4-period rolling mean + 95% CI. Flag only stages where this period is outside CI OR moves &gt;5pp absolute. Output JSON of flags with stage, this_value, baseline, delta, direction. No interpretation.</p>

        <p>Root-cause hypothesis: For each flag in the input: produce 2-3 hypotheses ranked by likelihood. For each hypothesis: required evidence to confirm + required evidence to falsify + the cheapest data source. Do not recommend actions yet. Refuse to invent numbers.</p>

        <p>A/B plan: Convert each accepted action into an experiment: hypothesis, primary metric, secondary, MDE, sample-size n per arm at 80% power, randomization unit, duration estimate, kill switches. Output one row per action.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="cli-tools">
        <list>
          <item>`gh` + GitHub Pages / `markdown-it` — Version-control funnel reports as artefacts</item>
          <item>Greenhouse Harvest API — Stage-by-stage candidate exports</item>
          <item>Lever API v1 — Same for Lever</item>
          <item>Ashby API — Stage transitions with timestamps</item>
          <item>`pandas` + `numpy` + `scipy.stats` — Conversion tests, CI math</item>
          <item>`dbt` + `duckdb` — Light warehousing if pulling multiple ATSes</item>
          <item>`metabase` (CLI / API) — Dashboards over the warehoused funnel</item>
          <item>Google Analytics 4 / `bq` — Career-page top-of-funnel</item>
          <item>LinkedIn Recruiter API / Talent Insights — Source-effectiveness</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="services-and-ats">
        <p>Greenhouse (SaaS ATS, agent-friendly with Harvest REST + webhooks): Strongest stage-transition logging. Lever (SaaS ATS, agent-friendly): Funnel reports out-of-box. Ashby (SaaS ATS, agent-friendly): Built-in funnel analytics; cleanest API. Workable (SaaS ATS, agent-friendly): SMB-friendly funnel views. iCIMS / Workday (SaaS ATS enterprise, partial agent-friendly): Heavy APIs; rate-limited. Datapeople / Beamery (SaaS analytics, agent-friendly REST): TA-specific funnel BI. Gem / SeekOut (SaaS sourcing, agent-friendly REST): Top-of-funnel sourcing intelligence. Eightfold (SaaS AI, agent-friendly REST): AI matching; bias audits required. LinkedIn Talent Insights (SaaS, limited agent-friendly): Market supply/demand. Glassdoor / Indeed analytics (SaaS, agent-friendly): Career-page traffic + apply rate. Calendly / GoodTime (SaaS, agent-friendly REST): Scheduling-stage data. BrightHire (SaaS, agent-friendly): Interview-stage drop-off + reason coding.</p>
      </section>

      <section name="best-practices">
        <list>
          <item>Segment funnel by role family (eng, sales, GA), level, and source. A blended funnel hides everything that matters.</item>
          <item>Always plot quality-of-hire (12-month performance) alongside conversion. Volume optimization at the cost of quality is a regression.</item>
          <item>Tag every reject reason at every stage with a controlled vocabulary (15-20 codes max). Free-text reasons are agent-uncodable in practice.</item>
          <item>Track time-in-stage, not just conversion. A 90% screen-to-interview that takes 21 days is worse than 70% in 4 days.</item>
          <item>Run a candidate experience survey at offer-decline and at hire — short, NPS plus 2 free-text. Sub-8-question surveys finish.</item>
          <item>For the 4 weeks after any process change, treat metrics as unstable. Pre-register the change and the expected lift in a doc the agent can later check.</item>
          <item>Compensation: keep a market-data refresh (Levels.fyi / Radford / Mercer) on a quarterly cadence. Offer-stage leaks are usually 6+ months stale data.</item>
          <item>Speed: time from final-interview to offer is the highest-leverage variable in offer acceptance for senior roles.</item>
          <item>Onboarding 90-day retention belongs in the funnel; if you optimize through offer-acceptance you're optimizing the wrong objective.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="agent-gotchas">
        <list>
          <item>LLMs cite "industry benchmarks" with confidence regardless of role, geo, or level. Always pin the benchmark source in the prompt; reject any unsourced number in output.</item>
          <item>Agents will "explain" any drop-off with a comp/speed/clarity narrative. Force evidence-required prompting; reject unsupported narratives in review.</item>
          <item>Funnel data has stage-name drift across ATSes ("Phone Screen" vs "Recruiter Screen" vs "Initial"). Pre-normalize with a mapping file or the LLM will count duplicates as separate stages.</item>
          <item>Drop-off attribution is multi-causal; agents will pick a single cause. Require ranked hypotheses with evidence requirements, never one root cause.</item>
          <item>An agent computing CI on weekly samples without checking n will report "significant" deltas at n=4. Block if n &lt; 8 per group.</item>
          <item>Action recommendations from LLMs default to "improve communication" and "review compensation" — both unmeasurable. Force every action into an A/B-testable form.</item>
          <item>Mandatory human-in-loop: (1) sign-off on the stage taxonomy, (2) approval of any compensation-band action (legal, equity, payroll cascade), (3) any change to JD or sourcing channel mix that touches budget.</item>
          <item>Career-page A/B tests must respect existing analytics consent banner; agents that auto-launch experiments without reading the privacy posture create GDPR liability.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/funnel-report.md" purpose="Monthly/quarterly funnel dashboard with conversion table and drop-off analysis."/>
    </templates>

